{
  "doc_id": "46801",
  "text": "Our results have shown that women who underwent surgical evacuation had thinner EMT than those who did not. Although it had a wide range of applications, the surgical evacuation, which could lead to the altering secretion of inflammatory cytokines and the thinning of endometrium, was usually considered as a damage factor of endometrium in the previous study [CITATION_1] . A retrospective study found that surgical evacuation was revealed as a cause for endometrial thinning in miscarriage [CITATION_2] . It was found that iatrogenic damage such as repeated or vigorous curettage might be the reason for thin endometrium and repeated surgical evacuation wound played an increasingly important role in gradual endometrial thinning [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Based on these studies, it could be considered that surgical evacuation has a direct association with EMT reduction.",
